.TH "WEAKMAP.HAS" "3JS" "September 22, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
WeakMap.has \- WeakMap.prototype.has()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]has()\f[B]\f[R] method of \f[CR]WeakMap\f[R] instances
returns a boolean indicating whether an entry with the specified key
exists in this \f[CR]WeakMap\f[R] or not.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] weakmap = \f[B]new\f[R] WeakMap();
\f[B]const\f[R] object1 = {};
\f[B]const\f[R] object2 = {};

weakmap.set(object1, \(dqfoo\(dq);

console.log(weakmap.has(object1));
\f[I]// Expected output: true\f[R]

console.log(weakmap.has(object2));
\f[I]// Expected output: false\f[R]
.EE
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
has(key)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]key\f[R]
The key of the entry to test for presence in the \f[CR]WeakMap\f[R]
object.
Object keys are compared by reference, not by value.
.SS Return value
Returns \f[CR]true\f[R] if an entry with the specified key exists in the
\f[CR]WeakMap\f[R] object; otherwise \f[CR]false\f[R].
Always returns \f[CR]false\f[R] if \f[CR]key\f[R] is not an object or a
non\-registered symbol.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using has()
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] wm = \f[B]new\f[R] WeakMap();
wm.set(window, \(dqfoo\(dq);

wm.has(window); \f[I]// returns true\f[R]
wm.has(\(dqbaz\(dq); \f[I]// returns false\f[R]
.EE
